04559nam a2200661Ia 9780801470998DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979740591  a97808014709987 a10.7591/97808014709982doi  a(DE-B1597)478263  a(OCoLC)877868588  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBX4901.3b.S66 2016 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a284.32231 aSomerset, Fiona, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFeeling Like Saints :bLollard Writings after Wyclif /cFiona Somerset. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart One -- t1. The Lollard Pastoral Program -- t2. God’s Law: Loving, Learning, and Teaching -- t3. Lollard Prayer: Religious Practice and Everyday Life -- tPart Two -- t4. Lollard Tales -- t5. Lollard Parabiblia -- tPart Three -- t6. Moral Fantasie: Normative Allegory in Lollard Writings -- t7. Lollard Forms of Living -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"Lollard" is the name given to followers of John Wyclif, the English dissident theologian who was dismissed from Oxford University in 1381 for his arguments regarding the eucharist. A forceful and influential critic of the ecclesiastical status quo in the late fourteenth century, Wyclif's thought was condemned at the Council of Constance in 1415. While lollardy has attracted much attention in recent years, much of what we think we know about this English religious movement is based on records of heresy trials and anti-lollard chroniclers. In Feeling Like Saints, Fiona Somerset demonstrates that this approach has limitations. A better basis is the five hundred or so manuscript books from the period (1375–1530) containing materials translated, composed, or adapted by lollard writers themselves.These writings provide rich evidence for how lollard writers collaborated with one another and with their readers to produce a distinctive religious identity based around structures of feeling. Lollards wanted to feel like saints. From Wyclif they drew an extraordinarily rigorous ethic of mutual responsibility that disregarded both social status and personal risk. They recalled their commitment to this ethic by reading narratives of physical suffering and vindication, metaphorically martyring themselves by inviting scorn for their zeal, and enclosing themselves in the virtues rather than the religious cloister. Yet in many ways they were not that different from their contemporaries, especially those with similar impulses to exceptional holiness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aLollardsvSources. 0aLollardsxSources. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  areligious texts, heresy, medieval religion, medieval christianity, history of religion, english theology, ecclesiastical status quo, council of constance, lollardy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147099840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801470998423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801470998/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles